Define Documentation

#define ExtFfsFileType (  type_name   )     ((FfsFileType)FFS_FILETYPE_##type_name)
 

This macro allows the client to use project specific file types which are defined at FFS driver level but not mapped to the APOXI FfsFileType enumeration. E.g., if the FFS driver defines a project specific file type named FFS_FILETYPE_MY_FILETYPE_1 then you are able to use it all the same by applying the macro ExtFfsFileType(MY_FILETYPE_1). For supporting it on host you have to define the client specific file type to a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS file type value once before applying the macro since it is not defined in the FFS host simulator.

For managing the project specific file types we recommend generating a dedicated header file which resides in some project specific configuration folder. In this header file all the project specific file types can be centrally defined as defines or constants which use the naming scheme of the APOXI FfsFileType enumeration, e.g.

        #if defined(APOXI_RTOS_WIN32)
            // This has to be a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS
            // file type value.
            #define FFS_FILETYPE_MY_FILETYPE_1 (FfsFileTypeAll + 1)
        #endif

        #define FfsFileTypeMyFiletype1 ExtFfsFileType(MY_FILETYPE_1)

or

        #if defined(APOXI_RTOS_WIN32)
            // This has to be a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS
            // file type value.
            #define FFS_FILETYPE_MY_FILETYPE_1 (FfsFileTypeAll + 1)
        #endif

        const FfsFileType FfsFileTypeMyFiletype1 =
            ExtFfsFileType(MY_FILETYPE_1);

Each file using those project specific file types shall include this header file and is then able to specify the file type as if it was one of the APOXI defined file types, e.g. FfsFileTypeMyFiletype1 for the example given above.

#define ExtFfsPit (  pit_name   )     ((FfsPit)FFS_##pit_name)
 

This macro allows the client to use project specific PITs which are defined at FFS driver level but not mapped to the APOXI FfsPit enumeration. E.g., if the FFS driver defines a project specific PIT named FFS_PIT_MY_PIT_1 then you are able to use it all the same by applying the macro ExtFfsPit(FFS_PIT_MY_PIT_1). For supporting it on host you have to define the client specific PIT to a unique integral value not yet used as a PIT value once before applying the macro since it is not defined in the FFS host simulator. This value has to be lower than FfsNofResId.

For managing the project specific PITs we recommend generating a dedicated header file which resides in some project specific configuration folder. In this header file all the project specific PITs can be centrally defined as defines or constants which use the naming scheme of the APOXI FfsPit enumeration, e.g.

        #if defined(APOXI_RTOS_WIN32)
            // This has to be a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS
            // PIT value. This value has to be lower than FfsNofResId.
            #define FFS_PIT_MY_PIT_1 (FfsNofResId - 1)
        #endif

        #define FfsPitMyPit1 ExtFfsPit(PIT_MY_PIT_1)

or

        #if defined(APOXI_RTOS_WIN32)
            // This has to be a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS
            // PIT value. This value has to be lower than FfsNofResId.
            #define FFS_PIT_MY_PIT_1 (FfsNofResId - 1)
        #endif

        const FfsPit FfsPitMyPit1 = ExtFfsPit(PIT_MY_PIT_1);

Each file using those project specific PITs shall include this header file and is then able to specify the PIT as if it was one of the APOXI defined PITs, e.g. FfsPitMyPit1 for the example given above.

#define ExtFfsUserType (  type_name   )     ((FfsUserType)FFS_##type_name)
 

This macro allows the client to use project specific user types which are defined at FFS driver level but not mapped to the APOXI FfsUserType enumeration. E.g., if the FFS driver defines a project specific user type named FFS_MY_USER_1 then you are able to use it all the same on target by applying the macro ExtFfsUserType(MY_USER_1). For supporting it on host you have to define the client specific user type to a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS user type value once before applying the macro since it is not defined in the FFS host simulator.

For managing the project specific user types we recommend generating a dedicated header file which resides in some project specific configuration folder. In this header file all the project specific user types shall be centrally defined as defines or constants which use the naming scheme of the APOXI FfsUserType enumeration, e.g.

        #if defined(APOXI_RTOS_WIN32)
            // This has to be a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS
            // user type value.
            #define FFS_MY_USER_1 (FfsGarbageCollector + 1)
        #endif

        #define FfsUserTypeMyUser1 ExtFfsUserType(MY_USER_1)

or

        #if defined(APOXI_RTOS_WIN32)
            // This has to be a unique integral value not yet used as an FFS
            // user type value.
            #define FFS_MY_USER_1 (FfsGarbageCollector + 1)
        #endif

        const FfsUserType FfsUserTypeMyUser1 = ExtFfsUserType(MY_USER_1);

Each file using those project specific file types shall include this header file and is then able to specify the user type as if it was one of the APOXI defined user types, e.g. FfsUserTypeMyUser1 for the example given above.

typedef word FfsFileId
 

Type of a file ID.

typedef ffs_handle_type FfsHandle
 

FfsHandle controls the access to files. It is also responsible to prevent more processes to operate on a file simultaneously. When calling the FfsHandler::Create() or FfsHandler::Open() methods, a new file handle is created.

enum FfsFileType
 

FfsFileType defines the enumeration values for the currently supported filetypes in the FFS. For every filetype not listed here, the filetype FfsFileTypeGeneric should be used. The FFS then allocates memory from the global pool.

enum FfsOpenMode
 

FfsOpenMode defines the enumeration values for the different open-modes. There is no possibility to open a file in write-mode, since a file is implicitly open in write-mode only after creation. After the file is closed once, the only possible methods to change the content of a file are via FfsOpenModeModify or FfsOpenModeAppend.

Enumerator:
FfsOpenModeRead 
FfsOpenModeAppend 
FfsOpenModeModify 
FfsOpenModeReadStr 

enum FfsPit
 

PIT (Pre-assigned ID Table) enumeration: In the PIT it's possible to reserve some file-IDs at compile-time. These IDs can be used for files that are downloaded during production.

Enumerator:
FfsNofResId

    ((FFS_BLOCK_SIZE - c_ffs_block_header_size * 2) / FFS_SECTOR_SIZE) *
